## 3. RETRIEVAL/DATA-ACCESS MCP POSSIBILITIES

### MCP Resource Server Pattern

```typescript
// MCP Server exposes resources (documents, indexes)
interface MCPResourceServer {
  resourcePatterns: [
    "document://corpus/{id}",
    "index://embeddings/{namespace}",
    "chunk://vector/{hash}",
    "metadata://refs/{type}/{id}"
  ];

  // Client calls to fetch chunks at retrieval time
  async readResource(uri: string): Promise<string>;
}
```

**How it works in retrieval:**
1. Agent queries local retriever → gets chunk IDs/URIs
2. Chunk URIs point to MCP resources: `document://corpus/doc-123#chunk-5`
3. MCP server resolves URIs (could fetch from remote DB, file system, real-time indexing service)
4. Lazy-loaded retrieval = only fetch what's needed

**Advantages:**
- Decouples retrieval logic from storage
- Enables remote document servers without embedding them
- Supports real-time document updates
- Composable: multiple MCP servers = multiple corpora

### MCP Tool Patterns for Data Access

```typescript
// Retrieval tools via MCP
{
  name: "search_knowledge_base",
  description: "Search documents via vector similarity",
  input: {
    query: "string",
    topK: "number",
    filters: "{ namespace?: string, metadata?: Record }"
  }
}

{
  name: "fetch_document_chunk",
  description: "Fetch full content of a chunk",
  input: { chunkId: "string", expand?: "boolean" }
}

{
  name: "list_namespaces",
  description: "List available document namespaces/collections",
  input: {}
}
```

**Design pattern:**
- Retriever can chain MCP tool calls
- Enables ranking/filtering at retrieval server
- Reduces latency via server-side filtering

