## SUMMARY TABLE: Key Design Decisions

| Component | V1 Approach | Why | Future Evolution |
|-----------|-------------|-----|-----------------|
| **Vector Store** | Mock in-memory | No vendor lock-in; fast iteration | Pinecone, Weaviate, Milvus |
| **Embeddings** | Mock vectors | Defer API costs; mock works offline | OpenAI/Ollama/Anthropic adapters |
| **Retrieval** | BM25 + mock semantic | Deterministic; no model dependency | Dense retrieval + reranking |
| **Browser** | Local MCP + Playwright | Self-contained; debuggable | Remote MCP; headless farm |
| **Config** | YAML + env interpolation | Simple; tracks in git | Feature flags; remote config |
| **Secrets** | .env file | Standard Python/Node approach | HashiCorp Vault; AWS Secrets |
| **Evaluation** | Metrics on gold standard | Measurable quality | LLM-as-judge; human feedback loop |
| **Observability** | Structured JSON logs | Works without infrastructure | OpenTelemetry; distributed tracing |

---

This architecture prioritizes **pluggability, testability, and QA observability** while keeping V1 lean. The abstraction layers ensure you can swap implementations without core logic changes, and the MCP patterns enable both browser automation and future retrieval system integrations without hardcoding vendor choices.

